{"title_page": "Pat Chan", "text_new": "{{short description|Singaporean swimmer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|Chan}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Pat Chan\n| image          = Patricia Chan 1966.jpg\n| image_size     = 240px\n| caption        = Chan in 1966\n| full_name      = Patricia Chan Li-Yin\n| nationality    = Singapore\n| strokes        = [[Backstroke]], [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]], [[Medley swimming|Medley]]\n| club           = Chinese Swimming Club\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=y|1954|04|12}}\n| birth_place    = [[Singapore]]\n| height         = 1.73 m\n| weight         = 64 kg\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Women's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{SIN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|1970 Bangkok|[[1970 Asian Games|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|1970 Bangkok|[[1970 Asian Games|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|1970 Bangkok|[[1970 Asian Games|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1966 Bangkok|[[Swimming at the 1966 Asian Games|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1966 Bangkok|[[Swimming at the 1966 Asian Games|200 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1966 Bangkok|[[Swimming at the 1966 Asian Games|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1970 Bangkok|[[1970 Asian Games|100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1970 Bangkok|[[1970 Asian Games|200 m freestyle]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Patricia Chan Li-Yin''' (\u9648\u4e3d\u71d5; born 12 April 1954), popularly known as '''Pat Chan''' and the \"Golden Girl\", is a retired swimmer from Singapore. Between 1965 and 1973 she won 39 gold medals at [[Southeast Asian Games]], which was the best achievement for a Singaporean athlete in any sport until 2005. She competed in eight events at the [[1966 Asian Games|1966]] and [[1970 Asian Games]] and won 3 silver and 5 bronze medals.<ref name=AG/> At the 1970&nbsp;Games she set a national record in the 200&nbsp;m backstroke that stood for 23&nbsp;years. At the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] she was the [[List of flag bearers for Singapore at the Olympics|flag bearer for Singapore]] and competed in the 100&nbsp;m and 200&nbsp;m backstroke events, but failed to reach the finals.<ref name=r2/> Chan was named the Best Sportswoman of Singapore for five consecutive years (1967\u20131971).<ref name=r1/> In 2002, she was inducted into the Singapore Sports Council Hall of Fame and ranked fourth among Singapore's 50 greatest athletes.<ref name=r3/>\n\nChan retired from competitions in 1973, aged 19, to become the first Singaporean female professional coach. She later turned to journalism, and currently runs her own media company, Visus Inq.<ref name=r3/>\n\n==Family==\nPatricia and her siblings were coached by their father, [[Chan Ah Kow]], the Singaporean Coach of the Year in 1970 and 1971. Her brother [[Roy Chan|Roy Chan Kum Wah]], won a bronze medal at the [[1970 Asian Games]] in the 4\u00d7200&nbsp;m relay.<ref name=AG>{{cite web|url=http://www.singaporeolympics.com/files/Asian-Games-Winners3.pdf |title=Asian Games Winners |publisher=Singapore National Olympic Council |year=2002 |accessdate=2012-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412074517/http://www.singaporeolympics.com/files/Asian-Games-Winners3.pdf |archivedate=12 April 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19720313-1.2.35.aspx|title=Swimmer Roy also shines in studies|work=The Straits Times|date=1972-03-13|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19740717-1.2.45.aspx|title=Roy to unveil plaque at Ocean Building|work=The Straits Times|date=1974-07-17|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> Her two other brothers, Alex Chan Meng Wah and [[Bernard Chan (swimmer)|Bernard Chan Cheng Wah]], were swimmers too;  the latter competed at the [[1966 Asian Games]] and [[1964 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19780804-1.2.162.3.aspx|title=Swim star weds|work=The Straits Times|date=1978-08-04|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsmuseum.com.sg/olympism/asian_games/locations.html|title=Host Nations and Representatives for the Asian Games|publisher=Sports Museum of Singapore|accessdate=2012-11-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106045954/http://www.sportsmuseum.com.sg/olympism/asian_games/locations.html|archivedate=6 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Her other brother [[Mark Chan]] is a composer,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fridae.asia/newsfeatures/2004/03/22/30.little-night-music-with-pat-chan-march-26|title=Little night music with Pat Chan|work=Fridae Asia|date=2004-03-22|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://finance.cctv.com/special/C19252/20070905/102411.shtml|title=\u9648\u56fd\u534e|work=[[China Central Television]]|date=2007-09-05|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> while her elder sister, [[Victoria Chan-Palay]] is a prominent neuroscientist in the United States and Switzerland.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19750615\">{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19750615-1.2.6.aspx|first=Ranee|last=Govindram|title=Ex-swim star gets rare varsity honour; Harvard award for Dr. Chan's daughter Vicky|work=The Straits Times|date=1975-06-15|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref> Her niece, [[Marina Chan|Marina]], is an international swimmer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Toh Ting Wei|title=Marina keeps Chan name flying|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/sports/marina-keeps-chan-name-flying|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|location=[[Singapore]]|via=[[AsiaOne]]|date=11 June 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.sportsmuseum.com.sg/heroes/hall_of_fame/patricia_chan.html Patricia Chan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122145916/http://www.sportsmuseum.com.sg/heroes/hall_of_fame/patricia_chan.html |date=22 January 2014 }}. sportsmuseum.com.sg</ref>\n<ref name=r2>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ch/pat-chan-1.html Pat Chan]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n<ref name=r3>[http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1376_2010-04-29.html Patricia Chan Li-Yin] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219105610/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1376_2010-04-29.html |date=19 December 2013 }}. infopedia.nl.sg</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SNOC profile|patricia-chan|Patricia Chan}}\n* {{IOC profile|patricia-li-yin-chan|Patricia LI YIN-CHAN}}\n* {{Olympic Channel|patricia-li-yin-chan|Patricia LI YIN-CHAN}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan, Patricia}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Female backstroke swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Asian Games silver medalists for Singapore]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for Singapore]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1966 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1970 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1966 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1970 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for Singapore]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1970 British Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Singaporean female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games gold medalists for Singapore]]\n[[Category:Southeast Asian Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1971 Southeast Asian Peninsular Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Singaporean swimmer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|Chan}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Pat Chan\n| image          = Patricia Chan 1966.jpg\n| image_size     = 240px\n| caption        = Patricia Chan in 1966\n| fullname       = Patri